  "prompt": "Should I use two single pages, or both sides of a single piece of paper for a two-page resume?",
  "response": "Using both sides of a single piece of paper for a two-page resume is generally not recommended. Here are a few reasons why:\n\n1. **Professionalism**: It is more professional and standard to submit a resume printed on separate pages rather than back-to-back.\n\n2. **Ease of Reading**: Double-sided resumes can be harder to read and may inconvenience the reader who might prefer to see each page separately for easier handling.\n\n3. **Application Systems**: In many cases, resumes are scanned or uploaded into application systems that are designed to process single-sided documents. Double-sided pages can cause issues in such systems.\n\n4. **Consistency**: If you are applying to multiple places, consistency is key. It is best to adhere to common practices to ensure your resume is accepted everywhere without confusion.\n\nTherefore, it is advisable to print each page on a separate sheet of paper. This ensures a clean, professional presentation and avoids potential complications for the reader.",
